{"Body": "<p>\n</p><p>Last week, the US Department of Justice approved the controversial merger of two music industry giants; concert promoter Live Nation and ticket agent Ticketmaster. &nbsp;This follows the UK Competition Commission&rsquo;s approval of the merger in December, taking a U-turn on their previous claim that the merger was anti-competitive.</p>\n<p>This new superpower will control every aspect of the music industry from artist management (including U2, Madonna, Jay-Z, the Eagles), distribution and promotion of events, tickets sales and venue ownership, with all the extras like T-shirts and beer sales, parking etc. &nbsp;Michael Rapino, chief executive of Live Nation and the newly merged company, said the coming together would create &ldquo;a more diversified company with a great selling platform for artists and a stronger financial profile that will drive improved shareholder value over the long term&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>However there is widespread concern that the new company will dominate the market, pushing up prices for the consumer.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The DOJ-approved merger contains modifications to the originally proposed merger to the effect that Ticketmaster will have to licence a copy of its ticketing software and sell its Paciola ticketing company to other &ldquo;suitable&rdquo; companies. According to the DOJ, these moves will recreate the level of competition that existed in the live music marketplace before the merger of Live Nation and Ticketmaster.</p>\n<p>Independent promoters, music journalists, bloggers and the wider public remain sceptical.</p>\n<div></div>\n", "Imageurl": "<p>\n</p><p>Last week, the US Department of Justice approved the controversial merger of two music industry giants; concert promoter Live Nation and ticket agent Ticketmaster. &nbsp;This follows the UK Competition Commission&rsquo;s approval of the merger in December, taking a U-turn on their previous claim that the merger was anti-competitive.</p>\n<p>This new superpower will control every aspect of the music industry from artist management (including U2, Madonna, Jay-Z, the Eagles), distribution and promotion of events, tickets sales and venue ownership, with all the extras like T-shirts and beer sales, parking etc. &nbsp;Michael Rapino, chief executive of Live Nation and the newly merged company, said the coming together would create &ldquo;a more diversified company with a great selling platform for artists and a stronger financial profile that will drive improved shareholder value over the long term&rdquo;.</p>\n<p>However there is widespread concern that the new company will dominate the market, pushing up prices for the consumer.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The DOJ-approved merger contains modifications to the originally proposed merger to the effect that Ticketmaster will have to licence a copy of its ticketing software and sell its Paciola ticketing company to other &ldquo;suitable&rdquo; companies. According to the DOJ, these moves will recreate the level of competition that existed in the live music marketplace before the merger of Live Nation and Ticketmaster.</p>\n<p>Independent promoters, music journalists, bloggers and the wider public remain sceptical.</p>\n<div></div>\n", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "629", "Heading": "US Department of Justice approves modified Live Nation, Ticketmaster merger"}